0for%20future%20reference" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Grok</a></div></div></div>


<div class="wp-block-group"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained">
<h2 id="why-youll-love-this-recipe"   class="wp-block-heading">Why You’ll Love This Recipe</h2>



<p>Korean Spicy Marinated Tofu recipe is inspired by the addicting <em>Yangnyeom (means spicy sauce</em>) flavor that is used to season Korean raw marinated crab—without the crab. The silken tofu texture is similar to soft poached eggs and the Korean spicy sauce is thick and packed with umami flavor. This recipe is <strong>great for vegetarians</strong> and meat lovers, because the sauce is truly so addicting with the Korean red pepper flakes, garlic and sesame oil! </p>



<p>The spicy sauce is so versatile that you can use on soft boiled eggs, raw marinated crab crab, <a href="https://cookwithdana.com/how-to-make-salmon-sashimi/">raw salmon sashimi</a> (my favorite method), or on top of white rice. </p>



<p>If you want more easy simple tofu recipes, check out my <a href="https://cookwithdana.com/chinese-stuffed-tofu-hakka-style/">Chinese Stuffed Tofu – Hakka Style</a>, <a href="https://cookwithdana.com/tofu-with-black-bean-sauce/">Tofu with Black Bean Sauce</a> and <a href="https://cookwithdana.com/easy-tofu-miso-soup/">Easy Tofu Miso Soup</a>.</p>
</div></div>
</div></div>


<style></style><details id="feast-advanced-jump-to"open><summary>Jump to:</summary><ul id="feast-jump-to-list"><li><a href="#%f0%9f%94%8d-quick-look">🔍 Quick Look: </a></li><li><a href="#why-youll-love-this-recipe">Why You’ll Love This Recipe</a></li><li><a href="#key-ingredients">Key Ingredients</a></li><li><a href="#substitutions-and-variations">Substitutions and Variations</a></li><li><a href="#how-to-make-korean-spicy-marinated-tofu">How to Make Korean Spicy Marinated Tofu</a></li><li><a href="#expert-tips">Expert Tips</a></li><li><a href="#korean-marinated-tofu-faqs">Korean Marinated Tofu FAQs</a></li><li><a href="#more-quick-and-easy-tofu-recipes">More Quick and Easy Tofu Recipes:</a></li><li><a href="#korean-spicy-marinated-tofu">Korean Spicy Marinated Tofu</a></li></ul></details>


<div class="wp-block-group"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained">
<h2 id="key-ingredients"   class="wp-block-heading" >Key Ingredients</h2>



<p>Here’s a look at what you need to make this&nbsp;<strong>Korean Spicy Marinated Tofu</strong>. The highlights are here but the full ingredient list and quantities of each are in the recipe card.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1600" height="1200" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201600%201200'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="" class="wp-image-14608" data-lazy-srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients.jpg 1600w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients-1024x768.jpg 1024w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients-500x375.jpg 500w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px" data-lazy-src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1600" height="1200" src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-14608" srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients.jpg 1600w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients-1024x768.jpg 1024w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-ingredients-500x375.jpg 500w" sizes="(max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px" /></noscript></figure>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Silken tofu</strong> &#8211; I love the soft tofu texture as it resembles the luscious texture of raw marinated crab (where this recipe was inspired from). I am using the <strong>soon tofu</strong> used for <a href="https://cookwithdana.com/korean-seafood-tofu-soup/">Korean Soft Tofu Stew</a> that I bought at the Korean market. You can use <strong>soft tofu or silken tofu</strong> for this recipe. </li>



<li><strong>Green onion</strong> &#8211; thinly sliced green onions soften up and provide a nice mild onion flavor to the silken tofu. You can use leeks or white onion flavors (sliced thinly), if that is what you have on hand. </li>



<li><strong>Grated garlic</strong> &#8211; the texture of finely minced garlic melts into the spicy sauce and provides that sweet and umami flavor. If your garlic is chopped, there may be a difference in texture. </li>



<li><strong>Gochugaru </strong>known as korean red pepper flakes is recommended for this spicy sauce. You can get mild or spicy gochugaru depending on your spice preference. You can&#8217;t substitute with red chili flakes or cayenne as the authentic Korean flavor won&#8217;t taste the same. </li>



<li><strong>Honey</strong> or sugar is used to balance the spicy and salty flavor. This is a must for authentic Korean flavor!</li>



<li><strong>Fish sauce is preferred for the umami flavor. </strong>You can sub with soy sauce if you&#8217;re vegetarian, still tastes delicious (I tried both variations).</li>



<li>Sesame oil &#8211; is a must for flavor! The nutty sesame oil balances the sweet and spicy flavors so well, I recommend buying the Kadoya brand I have above for best flavor.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>



<div class="wp-block-group"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained">
<h2 id="substitutions-and-variations"   class="wp-block-heading">Substitutions and Variations</h2>



<ul class="wp-block-list feast-feature">
<li>Add in Chinese chives, cucumbers, and carrots if you want some <strong>crunchy texture. </strong>Just make sure you adjust the sauce seasoning so your tofu is not too bland.</li>



<li><strong>Adjust your heat level.</strong> Every gochugaru brand is different and can be spicier than others, so adjust to your taste. Keep in mind that the texture might not look the same as my recipe if you&#8217;re using less. Still delicious nonetheless!</li>



<li>Add in <strong>soft boiled eggs</strong> as they have very similar texture to the tofu. The spicy eggs will taste delicious marinated overnight or served alongside this sauce. </li>
</ul>
</div></div>



<div class="wp-block-group"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained">
<h2 id="how-to-make-korean-spicy-marinated-tofu"   class="wp-block-heading" >How to Make&nbsp;Korean Spicy Marinated Tofu</h2>



<div class="wp-block-columns is-layout-flex wp-container-core-columns-is-layout-9d6595d7 wp-block-columns-is-layout-flex">
<div class="wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1600" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201200%201600'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="A bowl of chopped green onions and grated garlic." class="wp-image-14609" data-lazy-srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1.jpg 1200w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-225x300.jpg 225w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-720x960.jpg 720w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-360x480.jpg 360w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-180x240.jpg 180w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" data-lazy-src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1600" src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1.jpg" alt="A bowl of chopped green onions and grated garlic." class="wp-image-14609" srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1.jpg 1200w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-225x300.jpg 225w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-720x960.jpg 720w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-360x480.jpg 360w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-1-180x240.jpg 180w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></noscript></figure>



<p><strong>Step 1: </strong>Slice green onions and grate garlic.</p>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1600" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201200%201600'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Mixed Korean marinade ingredients including gochugaru, honey, fish sauce, sesame oil, sesame seeds, green onions, and garlic in a bowl with a spoon." class="wp-image-14610" data-lazy-srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2.jpg 1200w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-225x300.jpg 225w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-720x960.jpg 720w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-360x480.jpg 360w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-180x240.jpg 180w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" data-lazy-src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1600" src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2.jpg" alt="Mixed Korean marinade ingredients including gochugaru, honey, fish sauce, sesame oil, sesame seeds, green onions, and garlic in a bowl with a spoon." class="wp-image-14610" srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2.jpg 1200w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-225x300.jpg 225w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-720x960.jpg 720w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-360x480.jpg 360w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-2-180x240.jpg 180w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></noscript></figure>



<p><strong>Step 2: </strong>To make the sauce, combine gochugaru, honey, fish sauce (or soy sauce), sesame oil, sesame seeds, sliced green onions, and grated garlic until well combined.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div></div>



<div class="wp-block-columns is-layout-flex wp-container-core-columns-is-layout-9d6595d7 wp-block-columns-is-layout-flex">
<div class="wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1600" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201200%201600'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Silken tofu placed in a pot of water for boiling." class="wp-image-14611" data-lazy-srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3.jpg 1200w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-225x300.jpg 225w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-720x960.jpg 720w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-360x480.jpg 360w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-180x240.jpg 180w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" data-lazy-src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1600" src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3.jpg" alt="Silken tofu placed in a pot of water for boiling." class="wp-image-14611" srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3.jpg 1200w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-225x300.jpg 225w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-720x960.jpg 720w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-360x480.jpg 360w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-3-180x240.jpg 180w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></noscript></figure>



<p><strong>Step 3: </strong>Boil silken tofu for in boiling water for 2 minutes.</p>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1600" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201200%201600'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Drained silken tofu on a strainer next to a pot of water with tofu." class="wp-image-14612" data-lazy-srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4.jpg 1200w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-225x300.jpg 225w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-720x960.jpg 720w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-360x480.jpg 360w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-180x240.jpg 180w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" data-lazy-src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1600" src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4.jpg" alt="Drained silken tofu on a strainer next to a pot of water with tofu." class="wp-image-14612" srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4.jpg 1200w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-225x300.jpg 225w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-720x960.jpg 720w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-360x480.jpg 360w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/step-4-180x240.jpg 180w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></noscript></figure>



<p><strong>Step 4:</strong> Strain the tofu well so the water doesn’t get into the sauce.</p>
</div>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-columns is-layout-flex wp-container-core-columns-is-layout-9d6595d7 wp-block-columns-is-layout-flex">
<div class="wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1600" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201200%201600'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Sliced silken tofu in a spicy, savory Korean sauce with green onions and sesame seeds served in a glass bowl." class="wp-image-14613" data-lazy-srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto.jpg 1200w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-225x300.jpg 225w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-720x960.jpg 720w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-360x480.jpg 360w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-180x240.jpg 180w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" data-lazy-src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1600" src="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto.jpg" alt="Sliced silken tofu in a spicy, savory Korean sauce with green onions and sesame seeds served in a glass bowl." class="wp-image-14613" srcset="https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto.jpg 1200w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-225x300.jpg 225w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-720x960.jpg 720w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-360x480.jpg 360w, https://cookwithdana.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/korean-spicy-marinated-tofu-lastphoto-180x240.jpg 180w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></noscript></figure>



<p><strong>Step 5:</strong> In a airtight container, add tofu and your spicy sauce on top. Marinate for at least 1 hour to overnight for the best flavor (you can also eat right away if you can&#8217;t resist like me hehe). Enjoy with hot rice, noodles or vegetables!</p>
</div>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-group is-style-group-lightbulb"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained">
<h2 id="expert-tips"   class="wp-block-heading">Expert Tips</h2>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Drain thoroughly:</strong> Make sure to strain the tofu completely after boiling. Any leftover water can dilute the marinade and weaken the flavor.</li>



<li><strong>Handle tofu gently:</strong> Silken tofu is delicate, so slice and transfer it carefully to avoid breaking it before or after boiling.</li>



<li>If you have extra time, <strong>marinating the tofu overnight</strong> makes the tofu extra delicious. The flavor penetrates into the tofu and makes it saltier &amp; sweeter. </li>
</ul>
</div></div>



<div class="wp-block-group"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained">
<h2 id="korean-marinated-tofu-faqs"   class="wp-block-heading" >Korean Marinated Tofu FAQs</h2>



<div class="schema-faq wp-block-yoast-faq-block"><div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1769170204180"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Can I make this Korean marinated tofu vegan?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Yes, you can replace fish sauce with soy sauce or tamari for a vegan-friendly option that still gives the marinade a savory, umami kick.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1769170434228"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Can I use any types of tofu for Korean marinated tofu?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Yes, you can use soft tofu or regular tofu depending on what texture you like. I prefer the silken tofu because I love how silky and smooth it is! </p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1769459162881"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Can I meal prep Korean Marinated Tofu? </strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Yes, this recipe is <strong>great for meal prep</strong>. The flavors of the tofu become more salty and delicious as the days go by. The texture of the tofu doesn&#8217;t change and can be kept in the fridge for up to 4 days in an airtight container. </p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1658401249599"><strong class="schema-faq-question"><strong>What’s the best way to serve marinated tofu?</strong></strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Korean marinated tofu goes great with rice, nori, kimchi or noodles, and serving it alongside hearty dishes like <a href="https://cookwithdana.com/korean-pork-belly-samgyeopsal/">Korean Pork Belly BBQ</a>, <a href="https://cookwithdana.com/kimchi-fried-rice-with-spam/">One Pot Kimchi Fried Rice With Spam</a> or <a href="https://cookwithdana.com/japchae-potstickers/">Japchae Potstickers</a> makes for a full Korean-inspired meal! </p> </div> </div>
</div></div>



<div class="wp-block-group"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained">
<h2 id="more-quick-and-easy-tofu-recipes"   class="wp-block-heading" >More Quick and Easy Tofu Recipes:</h2>


